President Joe Biden has declared a state of emergency in New Jersey due to the remnants of Hurricane Ida. This declaration allows the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) to coordinate disaster relief efforts and provide assistance to alleviate the hardships caused by the emergency. FEMA is authorized to mobilize equipment and resources to help mitigate the impacts of the emergency. The federal government will provide 75% funding for emergency protective measures such as mass care and evacuation support. Patrick Cornhill has been named as the Federal Coordinating Officer for recovery operations in the affected areas. For more information, the media can contact the FEMA News Desk.